{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504518"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:16:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:16:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2339"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2339"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.01,0.16,0.64,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2339"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86764"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2339"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2339"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71034"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"3543"},{"type":"tags","id":"3572"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11539"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1254"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42471"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43129"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86764"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic five months after delivering her first baby. She reports feeling anxious with frequent night waking during the first two to three months postpartum, which she attributed to breastfeeding demands. During this period she experienced weight loss, but has gained 3 kg in the past month. She reports increasing constipation but normal appetite. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 56/min, blood pressure 125/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Thyroid examination is normal. Heart and lung examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Generalised anxiety disorder","Graves\u0027 disease","Postpartum depression","Postpartum thyroiditis","Sheehan syndrome"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is classic for \u003Cstrong\u003Epostpartum thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E, demonstrating a biphasic pattern. The initial phase (2-6 months postpartum) presents with thyrotoxicosis symptoms including anxiety and weight loss. This is followed by a hypothyroid phase (3-12 months postpartum) characterised by constipation, weight gain, bradycardia, and diastolic hypertension. The condition is typically self-limiting with spontaneous resolution within 12-18 months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneralised anxiety disorder\u003C/strong\u003E requires persistent, excessive worry about multiple aspects of life for at least 6 months. While this patient experienced anxiety symptoms, their timing and resolution, along with the physical findings of bradycardia and diastolic hypertension, make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraves\u0027 disease\u003C/strong\u003E causes persistent hyperthyroidism with symptoms such as tachycardia, tremor, and heat intolerance. The biphasic pattern seen here, with current bradycardia and weight gain, is inconsistent with Graves\u0027 disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPostpartum depression\u003C/strong\u003E can present with sleep disturbance, anxiety, and appetite changes. However, it would not explain the physical findings of bradycardia and diastolic hypertension characteristic of hypothyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESheehan syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by pituitary necrosis, presents with multiple hormone deficiencies including inability to breastfeed (prolactin deficiency) and hypotension (cortisol deficiency). This patient\u0027s successful breastfeeding and hypertension make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Postpartum thyroiditis typically presents with a hyperthyroid phase (2-6 months postpartum) followed by a hypothyroid phase (3-12 months postpartum).","Key symptoms of hypothyroid phase include constipation, weight gain, bradycardia, and diastolic hypertension.","Early hyperthyroid symptoms may be mistaken for normal postpartum anxiety or sleep deprivation."],"references":["Stagnaro-Green A. Postpartum thyroiditis. Best Practice \u0026 Research Clinical Endocrinology \u0026 Metabolism. 2004;18(2):303-316.","Smith A, Eccles-Smith J, D\u0027Emden M, Lust K. Thyroid disorders in pregnancy and postpartum. Aust Prescr. 2017;40(6):214-219. doi:10.18773/austprescr.2017.075"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71034"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2339"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71034"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"20